# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fungal-dna-barcoding
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] Along with the 28S and 5.8S rRNA in eukaryotes, the **18S rRNA** was early identified as integral structural element of ribosomes which were first characterized by their sedimentation properties and named according to measured Svedberg units.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] Given its ubiquitous presence in eukaryotic life, the evolution of the 18S rRNA was soon proposed as marker for phylogenetic studies to resolve the evolution of eukaryotes.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] The **18S ribosomal RNA** is the structural RNA of the small subunit in the eukaryotic cytoplasmic ribosome.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] The genomic sequence of the 18S rRNA is organized in a group with the 28S and 5.8S rRNA, separated and flanked by the ITS-1, ITS-2 and ETS spacer regions.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] These regions of ribosomal DNA (rDNA) are present with several hundred copies in the active genome, clustered in nucleolus organizer regions (NORs).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] In ribosome biogenesis, these genes are transcribed together by the RNA polymerase I and are processed in the nucleolus structure of the nucleus.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] The length of the 18S rRNA varies considerably in the eukaryotic phylogenetic tree, corresponding to a range of 16S-19S in Svedberg units, with the average length commonly given as around 2000 nucleotides.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] The 18S rRNA of humans has a length of 1869 nucleotides.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] The universal presence of the **18S rRNA** in eukaryotes and generally high degree of conservation in evolution allow the construction of universal primers for DNA amplification by polymerase chain reaction.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] The possible applications mirror molecular methods involving 16S rRNA of prokaryotes.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] Primers binding in highly conserved regions of the 18S rRNA are an important marker for biodiversity screening, allowing the amplification of unspecified or random targets from environmental samples as well as uncharacterized specimens from collections for DNA sequencing.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] Subsequent sequence alignment covering the less strictly conserved segments then allows the assignment of a sample to biologic clades.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] In the case of 18S rRNA, retrieval of DNA is improved by the abundance of repeating sequences of the rDNA within eukaryotic cells, promoting the sensitivity of the analysis.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] Multiple properties of the genomic sequence of the 18S rRNA have established it as an important marker gene for large-scale phylogenetic analysis and the reconstruction of the metazoan tree of life.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] The integral role in formation and function of the ribosome is a key cause for its omnipresence in eukaryotic life.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] Meanwhile, the gene maintains a high degree of conservation under a persistent selective pressure in all living beings, highlighting its potential for comparison between distantly related clades.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] Early studies utilizing the 18S rRNA sequence constructed the first large-scale phylogenetic trees of the metazoa.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] Evidence from further studies led to the creation of several important clades, such as the Ecdysozoa and Lophotrochozoa.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] During the latter part of the 2000s, and with increased numbers of taxa included into molecular phylogenies, however, two problems became apparent.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] First, there are prevailing sequencing impediments in representatives of certain taxa, such as the mollusk classes Solenogastres and Tryblidia, selected bivalve taxa, and the enigmatic crustacean class Remipedia.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] Failure to obtain 18S sequences of single taxa is considered a common phenomenon but is rarely ever reported.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] Secondly, in contrast to initially high hopes, 18S cannot resolve nodes at all taxonomic levels and its efficacy varies considerably among clades.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] This has been discussed as an effect of rapid ancient radiation within short periods.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/18s-ribosomal-rna] Multigene analyses are currently thought to give more reliable results for tracing deep branching events in Metazoa but 18S still is extensively used in phylogenetic analyses.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/28s-ribosomal-rna] Combined with 5.8S rRNA to the 5' side, it is the eukaryotic nuclear homologue of the prokaryotic 23S and mitochondrial 16S ribosomal RNAs.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/28s-ribosomal-rna] The genes coding for 28S rRNA are referred to as 28S rDNA.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/28s-ribosomal-rna] The comparison of the sequences from these genes are sometimes used in molecular analysis to construct phylogenetic trees, for example in protists, fungi, insects, arachnids, tardigrades, and vertebrates.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/28s-ribosomal-rna] The 28S rRNA is typically 4000–5000 nt long.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/28s-ribosomal-rna] Some eukaryotes cleave 28S rRNA into two parts before assembling both into the ribosome, a phenomenon termed the "hidden break".
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] In molecular biology, the **5.8S ribosomal RNA** (**5.8S rRNA**) is a non-coding RNA component of the large subunit of the eukaryotic ribosome and so plays an important role in protein translation.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] It is transcribed by RNA polymerase I as part of the 45S precursor that also contains 18S and 28S rRNA.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] Its function is thought to be in ribosome translocation.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] It is also known to form covalent linkage to the p53 tumour suppressor protein.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] 5.8S rRNA can be used as a reference gene for miRNA detection.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] The 5.8S ribosomal RNA is used to better understand other rRNA processes and pathways in the cell.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] The 5.8S rRNA is homologous to the 5' end of non-eukaryotic LSU rRNA.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] In eukaryotes, the insertion of ITS2 breaks LSU rRNA into 5.8S and 28S rRNAs.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] Some flies have their 5.8 rRNA further split into two pieces at the 3' end, forming what is called 5.8S, ITS2a, and 2S.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] L567.5 rRNA structure is approximately 150 nucleotides in size and it consists of plenty of folded strands, some of which are presumed to be single stranded.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] This ribosomal RNA, along with the 28S and 5S rRNA as well as 46 ribosomal proteins, forms the ribosomal large subunit (LSU).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] The 5.8S rRNA is initially transcribed along with the 18S and 28S rRNA in the 45S preribosomal RNA, along with the ITS 1 and ITS 2 (Internal transcribed spacer) and a 5’ and 3’ ETS (External transcribed spacer).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] The 5.8S rRNA is located between the two ITS regions, with ITS1 separating it from the 18S rRNA in the 5' direction, and ITS2 separating it from the 28S rRNA in the 3' direction.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] The ITS and ETS are cleaved away during rRNA maturation.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] This is accomplished through a continuous cleavage pathway performed by both endonuclease and exonuclease enzymes, cutting the spacers at specific locations.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricomycotina] The class Bartheletiomycetes contains a single anomalous species of basidiomycete which grows on fallen leaves of *Ginkgo biloba*.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricomycotina] Some researchers suggest that this class should be included in Agaricomycotina.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] Some poisonous lookalikes in the wild, such as *Entoloma sinuatum*, may appear similar.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] *Agaricus bisporus* often grows in rich soil and compost.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] The pileus or cap of the original wild species is a pale grey-brown, with broad, flat scales on a paler background and fading toward the margins.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] It is first hemispherical before flattening out with maturity, typically measuring 5–10 centimetres (2–4 inches) in diameter.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] The narrow, crowded gills are free and initially pink, then red-brown, and finally a dark brown with a whitish edge from the cheilocystidia.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] The cylindrical stipe is up to 6 cm (2+1⁄2 in) tall by 1–2 cm (1⁄2–3⁄4 in) wide and bears a thick and narrow ring, which may be streaked on the upper side.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] The firm flesh is white, although it stains a pale pinkish-red on bruising.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] The spores are oval to round and measure approximately 4.5–5.5 μm × 5–7.5 μm, and the basidia usually two-spored, although two four-spored varieties have been described from the Mojave Desert and the Mediterranean, with predominantly heterothallic and homothallic lifestyles, respectively.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] A more common and less dangerous mistake is to confuse *Agaricus bisporus* with *A. xanthodermus*, an inedible mushroom found worldwide in grassy areas.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] *A. xanthodermus* has an odor reminiscent of phenol; its flesh turns yellow when bruised.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] This fungus causes nausea and vomiting in some people.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] The poisonous European species *Entoloma sinuatum* has a passing resemblance but has yellowish gills, turning pink, and lacks a ring.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] The common mushroom has a complicated taxonomic history.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] It was first described by English botanist Mordecai Cubitt Cooke in his 1871 *Handbook of British Fungi*, as a variety (var.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] Danish mycologist Jakob Emanuel Lange later reviewed a cultivar specimen, and dubbed it *Psalliota hortensis* var.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] In 1938, it was promoted to species status and renamed *Psalliota bispora*.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] Emil Imbach (1897–1970) imparted the current scientific name of the species, *Agaricus bisporus* after the genus *Psalliota* was renamed to *Agaricus* in 1946.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] The specific epithet *bispora* distinguishes the two-spored basidia from four-spored varieties.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] When marketed in its mature state, the mushroom is brown with a cap measuring 10–15 cm (4–6 in).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] This form is commonly sold under the names portobello, portabella, or portobella.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] This mushroom is widespread worldwide, fruiting from autumn to winter, especially in association with cypress, rich soil, compost, and manure.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] In 2022, world production of mushrooms (including truffles) was 48 million tonnes, led by China with 94% of the total (table).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] Japan and the United States were secondary producers.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] The earliest scientific description of the commercial cultivation of *A. bisporus* was made by French botanist Joseph Pitton de Tournefort in 1707.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] French agriculturist Olivier de Serres noted that transplanting mushroom mycelia would lead to the propagation of more mushrooms.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] Originally, cultivation was unreliable as mushroom growers would watch for good flushes of mushrooms in fields before digging up the mycelium and replanting them in beds of composted manure or inoculating 'bricks' of compressed litter, loam, and manure.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] Spawn collected this way contained pathogens, and crops would be infected or not grow.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] In 1893, sterilized, or pure culture, spawn was discovered and produced by the Pasteur Institute in Paris for cultivation on composted horse manure.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] Modern commercial varieties of the common agaricus mushroom were originally light brown.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] The white mushroom was discovered in 1925 growing among a bed of brown mushrooms at the Keystone Mushroom Farm in Coatesville, Pennsylvania.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] Louis Ferdinand Lambert, the farm's owner and a mycologist by training, brought the white mushroom back to his laboratory.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] As with the reception of white bread, it was seen as a more attractive food item and became grown and distributed.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] Similar to the commercial development history of the navel orange and Red Delicious apple, cultures were grown from the mutant individuals.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] Most cream-colored store mushrooms marketed today are products of this 1925 chance natural mutation.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] In a reference amount of 100 g (3.5 oz), raw white mushrooms provide 93 kilojoules (22 kilocalories) of food energy and are an excellent source (20% or more of the Daily Value, DV) of the B vitamins riboflavin, niacin, and pantothenic acid.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] Fresh mushrooms are also a good source (10–19% DV) of the dietary minerals phosphorus and potassium.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/agaricus-bisporus] While fresh *A. bisporus* only contains 0.2 micrograms (8 IU) of vitamin D per 100 g, the ergocalciferol (D2) content increases substantially to 11.2 micrograms (446 IU) after exposure to UV light.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] One of the main challenges of identifying diatoms is that it is often collected as a mixture of diatoms from several species.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] DNA metabarcoding is the process of identifying the individual species from a mixed sample of environmental DNA (also called eDNA) which is DNA extracted straight from the environment such as in soil or water samples.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] A newly applied method is diatom DNA metabarcoding which is used for ecological quality assessment of rivers and streams because of the specific response of diatoms to particular ecologic conditions.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Until now, several DNA markers have already been developed, mainly targeting the 18S rRNA.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Using the V4 hypervariable region of the ribosomal small subunit DNA (SSU rDNA), DNA-based identification was found to be more efficient than the classical morphology-based approach.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Other conserved regions in the genomes which are frequently used as marker genes are ribulose-1-5-bisphosphate carboxylase (rbcL), cytochrome oxidase I (cox1, COI), ITS and 28S.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] It has been shown repeatedly that the molecular data gained by diatom eDNA metabarcoding quite faithfully reflect the morphology-based biotic diatom indices and therefore provide a similar assessment of ecosystem status.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] In the meantime, diatoms are routinely used for the assessment of ecological quality in other freshwater ecosystems.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Together with aquatic invertebrates they are considered as the best indicators of disturbance related to physical, chemical or biological conditions of watercourses.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Numerous studies are using benthic diatoms for biomonitoring.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Because no ideal diatom DNA barcode was found, it has been proposed that different markers are used for different purposes.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Indeed, the highly variable cox1, ITS and 28S genes were considered more suitable for taxonomic studies, while more conserved 18S and rbcL genes seem more appropriate for biomonitoring.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Applying the DNA barcoding concept to diatoms promises great potential to resolve the problem of inaccurate species identification and thus facilitate analyses of the biodiversity of environmental samples.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Molecular methods based on the NGS technology almost always leads to a higher number of identified taxa whose presence could subsequently be verified by light microscopy.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Results of this study provides evidence that eDNA barcoding of diatoms is suitable for water quality assessment and could complement or improve traditional methods.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Stoeck et al. also showed that eDNA barcoding provides a more insight into diatom diversity or other protist communities and therefore could be used for ecological projection of global diversity.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] For example, inventories obtained from the molecular-based method were closer to those obtained by the morphology-based method when abundant species are in focus.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] DNA metabarcoding can also increase the taxonomic resolution and comparability across geographic regions, which is often difficult using morphological characters only.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Moreover, DNA-based identification allows extending the range of potential bioindicators, including the inconspicuous taxonomic groups that could be highly sensitive or tolerant to particular stressors.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Currently there is no consensus concerning methods for DNA preservation and isolation, the choice of DNA barcodes and PCR primers, nor agreement concerning the parameters of MOTU clustering and their taxonomic assignment.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Sampling and molecular steps need to be standardize through development studies.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] One of the major limitation is the availability of reference barcodes for diatoms species.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] The reference database of bioindicator taxa is far from complete despite the constant efforts of numerous national barcoding initiatives a lot of species are still lacking barcode information.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Furthermore, most existing metabarcoding data are only locally available and geographically scattered, which is hindering the development of globally useful tools.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Visco et al. estimated that no more than 30% of European diatoms species are currently represented in reference databases.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] For example, there is an important lack for a number of species from the Fennoscandian communities (especially acidophilic diatoms, such as *Eunotia incisa*).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] It has also been shown that taxonomic identification with DNA barcoding is not accurate above species level, to discriminate varieties for example (reference missing).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] This has yet to be done for the variety of pipelines used in molecular assessment of diatom communities in Europe.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Taxonomically validated databases, which includes accessible vouchers are also crucial for reliable taxa identification via NGS.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Additionally, primer bias is often found to be a major source of variation in barcoding and PCR primers efficiency can differ between diatoms species, i.e. some primers lead to a preferential amplification of one taxon over another.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] The inference of abundance from metabarcoding data is considered as one of the most difficult issues in environmental use.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] The number of generated sequences by HTS does not directly correspond to the number of specimen or biomass and that different species can produce different amount of reads, (for example, due to differences in the chloroplast size with the rbcL marker).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Vasselon et al. recently created a biovolume correction factor when using the rbcL marker.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] For example, *Achnanthidium minutissimum* has a small biovolume, and thus will generate less copies of the rbcL fragment (located in the chloroplast) than larger species.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] This correction factor, however, requires extensive calibration with each species own biovolume and has been tested only on a few species that far.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Fluctuations of gene copy number for other markers, such as the 18S marker, does not seem to be species specific, but have not been tested yet.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Barcoding marker usually combine hypervariable regions of the genome (to allow the distinction between species) with very conserved region (to insure a specificity to the target organism).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Several DNA markers, belonging to the nuclear, mitochondrial, and chloroplast genomes (rbcL, COI, ITS+5.8S, SSU, 18S...), have been designed and successfully used for diatoms identification with NGS.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] The 18S gene region has been widely used as a marker in other protist groups and Jahn et al. were the first to test the 18S gene region for diatoms barcoding.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Zimmerman et al. proposed a 390–410 bp long fragment of the 1800 bp long 18S rRNA gene locus as a barcode marker for the analysis of environmental samples with HTS. and discusses its use and limitations for diatom identification.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] This fragment includes the V4 subunit which is the largest and most complex of the highly variable regions within the 18S locus.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] They highlighted that this hypervariable region of the 18S gene have great potential for studying protist diversity at large scale but has limited efficiency to identification below species level or cryptic species.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] The rbcl gene is used for taxonomy studies (Trobajo et al.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] 2009) which benefits include that rarely any intragenomic variation and they are very easily aligned and compared.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] An open-access reference library, called R-Syst::diatom includes data for two barcodes (18S and rbcL).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] It is freely accessible through a website.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Kermmarec et al. also successfully used the rbcL gene for ecological assessment of diatoms.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] The rbcL marker is also easily aligned and compared.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Moniz and Kaczmarska investigated the amplification success of the SSU, COI, and ITS2 markers and found that the 300 – 400 bp ITS-2 + 5.8S fragment provided the highest success rate of amplification and good species resolution.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] This marker was subsequently used to separate morphologically defined species with a success rate of 99.5%.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Despite this amplification success, Zimmerman et al. criticised the use of ITS-2 due to intra-individual heterogeneity.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] It has been suggested that SSU or the rbcL (Mann et al., 2010) markers less heterogenous between individuals and therefore more beneficial when distinguishing between species.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Diatoms are routinely used as part of a suite of biomonitoring tools which must be monitored as part of the European Water Framework Directive.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Over the recent years, researchers have developed and standardised the tools for the metabarcoding and sequencing of diatoms, to complement the traditional assessment using microscopy, opening up a new avenue of biomonitoring for aquatic systems.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Using benthic diatoms through a method of next-generation sequencing approach to river biomonitoring revealed a good potential in it.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Many studies have shown that metabarcoding and HTS (high-throughput sequencing) can be utilized to estimate the quality status and diversity in freshwaters.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] As part of the Environment Agency, Kelly et al. has developed a DNA-based metabarcoding approach to assess diatom communities in rivers for the UK.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Vasselon et al. compared morphological and HTS approaches for diatoms and found that HTS gave a reliable indication of quality status for most rivers in terms of Specific Polluosensitivity Index (SPI).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Vasselon et al. also applied DNA metabarcoding of diatoms communities to the monitoring network of rivers on the tropical Island Mayotte (French DOM-TOM).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Rimet et al. also explored the possibility of using HTS for assessing diatom diversity and showed that diversity indices from both HTS and microscopic analysis were well correlated although not perfect.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] DNA barcoding and metabarcoding can be used to establish molecular metrics and indices, which potentially provide conclusions broadly similar to those of the traditional approaches about the ecological and environmental status of aquatic ecosystems.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Diatoms are used to as a diagnosis tool for drowning in forensic practices.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] The diatom test is based on the principle of diatom inhalation from water into the lungs and distribution and deposition around the body.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] DNA methods can be used to confirm if the cause of death was indeed drowning and locate the origin of drowning.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Diatom DNA metabarcoding, provides the opportunity to quickly analyse the diatom community present within a body and locate the origin of drowning and investigate if a body may have been moved from one place to another.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Diatom metabarcoding may help delimit cryptic species that are difficult to identify using microscopy and help complete reference databases by comparing morphological assemblages to metabarcoding data.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Chlorophytes possess an ancients and taxonomically very diverse lineage (Fang et al.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] 2014), including terrestrial plants too.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Even though more than 14 000 species have been described based on structural and ultrastructural criteria (Hall et al.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] 2010) their morphological identification is often limited.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Several barcodes for chlorophytes have been proposed for DNA-based identification in order to bypass the problematics of the morphological one.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Although the cytochrome oxidase I (COI, COX) coding gene (link) is a standard barcode for animals it proved to be unsatisfactory for chlorophytes because the gene contains several introns in this algae group (Turmel et al.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Nuclear marker genes have been used for chlorophytes are SSU rDNA, LSU rDNA, rDNA ITS (Leliaert et al.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Macroalgae—a morphological rather than taxonomic grouping—can be very challenging to identify because of their simple morphology, phenotypic plasticity and alternate lifecycle stages.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Thus, algal systematics and identification have come to rely heavily on genetic/molecular tools such as DNA barcoding.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] The SSU rDNA gene is a common used barcode for phylogenetic studies on macroalgae.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] However, the SSU rDNA is a highly conserved region and typically lack resolution for species identification.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Over the past 2 decades certain standards for DNA barcoding with the aim of species identification have been developed for each of the main groups of macroalgae.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] The cytochrome c oxidase subunit I (COI) gene is commonly used as a barcode for red and brown algae, while tufA (plastid elongation factor), rbcL (rubisco large subunit) and ITS (internal transcribe spacer) are commonly used for green algae.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] These barcodes are typically 600-700 bp long.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] The barcodes typically differ between the 3 main groups of macroalgae (red, green and brown) because their evolutionary heritage is very diverse.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/algae-dna-barcoding] Macroalgae is a polyphyletic group, meaning that within the group they do not all share a recent common ancestor, making it challenging to find a gene that is conserved among all but variable enough for species identification.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Amino acids can be classified according to the locations of the core structural functional groups (alpha- (α-), beta- (β-), gamma- (γ-) amino acids, etc.); other categories relate to polarity, ionization, and side-chain group type (aliphatic, acyclic, aromatic, polar, etc.).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] In the form of proteins, amino-acid *residues* form the second-largest component (water being the largest) of human muscles and other tissues.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Beyond their role as residues in proteins, amino acids participate in a number of processes such as neurotransmitter transport and biosynthesis.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] It is thought that they played a key role in enabling life on Earth and its emergence.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Amino acids are formally named by the IUPAC-IUBMB Joint Commission on Biochemical Nomenclature in terms of the fictitious "neutral" structure shown in the illustration.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] For example, the systematic name of alanine is 2-aminopropanoic acid, based on the formula CH3−CH(NH2)−COOH.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The first few amino acids were discovered in the early 1800s.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] In 1806, French chemists Louis-Nicolas Vauquelin and Pierre Jean Robiquet isolated a compound from asparagus that was subsequently named asparagine, the first amino acid to be discovered.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Cystine was discovered in 1810, although its monomer, cysteine, remained undiscovered until 1884.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Glycine and leucine were discovered in 1820.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The last of the 20 common amino acids to be discovered was threonine in 1935 by William Cumming Rose, who also determined the essential amino acids and established the minimum daily requirements of all amino acids for optimal growth.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The unity of the chemical category was recognized by Wurtz in 1865, but he gave no particular name to it.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The first use of the term "amino acid" in the English language dates from 1898, while the German term, *Aminosäure*, was used earlier.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Proteins were found to yield amino acids after enzymatic digestion or acid hydrolysis.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] In 1902, Emil Fischer and Franz Hofmeister independently proposed that proteins are formed from many amino acids, whereby bonds are formed between the amino group of one amino acid with the carboxyl group of another, resulting in a linear structure that Fischer termed "peptide".
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] 2-, alpha-, or α-amino acids have the generic formula H2NCHRCOOH in most cases, where R is an organic substituent known as a "side chain".
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Of the many hundreds of described amino acids, 22 are proteinogenic ("protein-building").
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] It is these 22 compounds that combine to give a vast array of peptides and proteins assembled by ribosomes.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids may arise through nonribosomal peptide synthesis.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Modified amino acids, by contrast, typically result from post-translational modification.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Amino acids with the structure NH+3−CXY−CXY−CO−2, such as β-alanine, a component of carnosine and a few other peptides, are β-amino acids.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Ones with the structure NH+3−CXY−CXY−CXY−CO−2 are γ-amino acids, and so on, where X and Y are two substituents (one of which is normally H).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The carbon atom next to the carboxyl group is called the α–carbon.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] In proteinogenic amino acids, it bears the amine and the R group or side chain specific to each amino acid, as well as a hydrogen atom.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] With the exception of glycine, for which the side chain is also a hydrogen atom, the α–carbon is stereogenic.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] All chiral proteinogenic amino acids have the L configuration.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] They are "left-handed" enantiomers, which refers to the stereoisomers of the alpha carbon.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] A few D-amino acids ("right-handed") have been found in nature, e.g., in bacterial envelopes, as a neuromodulator (D-serine), and in some antibiotics.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Rarely, D-amino acid residues are found in proteins, and are converted from the L-amino acid as a post-translational modification.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Five amino acids possess a charge at neutral pH.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Often these side chains appear at the surfaces on proteins to enable their solubility in water, and side chains with opposite charges form important electrostatic contacts called salt bridges that maintain structures within a single protein or between interfacing proteins.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Many proteins bind metal into their structures specifically, and these interactions are commonly mediated by charged side chains such as aspartate, glutamate and histidine.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Under certain conditions, each ion-forming group can be charged, forming double salts.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The two negatively charged amino acids at neutral pH are aspartate (Asp, D) and glutamate (Glu, E).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The anionic carboxylate groups behave as Brønsted bases in most circumstances.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Enzymes in very low pH environments, like the aspartic protease pepsin in mammalian stomachs, may have catalytic aspartate or glutamate residues that act as Brønsted acids.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] There are three amino acids with side chains that are cations at neutral pH: arginine (Arg, R), lysine (Lys, K) and histidine (His, H).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Arginine has a charged guanidino group and lysine a charged alkyl amino group, and are fully protonated at pH 7.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Histidine's imidazole group has a pKa of 6.0, and is only around 10% protonated at neutral pH.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Because histidine is easily found in its basic and conjugate acid forms it often participates in catalytic proton transfers in enzyme reactions.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The polar, uncharged amino acids serine (Ser, S), threonine (Thr, T), asparagine (Asn, N) and glutamine (Gln, Q) readily form hydrogen bonds with water and other amino acids.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] They do not ionize in normal conditions, a prominent exception being the catalytic serine in serine proteases.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] This is an example of severe perturbation, and is not characteristic of serine residues in general.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Threonine has two chiral centers, not only the L (2*S*) chiral center at the α-carbon shared by all amino acids apart from achiral glycine, but also (3*R*) at the β-carbon.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The full stereochemical specification is (2*S*,3*R*)-L-threonine.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Because of the presence of phenolic hydroxyl group with a pKa = ~10, tyrosine is best classified as a neutral polar amino acid, but with amphipathic character that makes it less polar than classical small polar amino acid residues.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Nonpolar amino acid interactions are the primary driving force behind the processes that fold proteins into their functional three dimensional structures.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] None of these amino acids' side chains ionize easily, and therefore do not have pKas.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Several side chains are not described well by the charged, polar and hydrophobic categories.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Glycine (Gly, G) could be considered a polar amino acid since its small size means that its solubility is largely determined by the amino and carboxylate groups.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] However, the lack of any side chain provides glycine with a unique flexibility among amino acids with large ramifications to protein folding.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Cysteine (Cys, C) can also form hydrogen bonds readily, which would place it in the polar amino acid category, though it can often be found in protein structures forming covalent bonds, called disulphide bonds, with other cysteines.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] These bonds influence the folding and stability of proteins, and are essential in the formation of antibodies.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Proline (Pro, P) has an alkyl side chain and could be considered hydrophobic, but because the side chain joins back onto the alpha amino group it becomes particularly inflexible when incorporated into proteins.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Similar to glycine this influences protein structure in a way unique among amino acids.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Selenocysteine (Sec, U) is a rare amino acid not directly encoded by DNA, but is incorporated into proteins via the ribosome.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Selenocysteine has a lower redox potential compared to the similar cysteine, and participates in several unique enzymatic reactions.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine (Pyl, O) is another amino acid not encoded in DNA, but synthesized into protein by ribosomes.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] It is found in archaeal species where it participates in the catalytic activity of several methyltransferases.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The 20 canonical amino acids can be classified according to their properties.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Important factors are charge, hydrophilicity or hydrophobicity, size, and functional groups.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] These properties influence protein structure and protein–protein interactions.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The water-soluble proteins tend to have their hydrophobic residues (Leu, Ile, Val, Phe, and Trp) buried in the middle of the protein, whereas hydrophilic side chains are exposed to the aqueous solvent.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] (In biochemistry, a residue refers to a specific monomer *within* the polymeric chain of a polysaccharide, protein or nucleic acid.) The integral membrane proteins tend to have outer rings of exposed hydrophobic amino acids that anchor them in the lipid bilayer.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Some peripheral membrane proteins have a patch of hydrophobic amino acids on their surface that sticks to the membrane.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] In a similar fashion, proteins that have to bind to positively charged molecules have surfaces rich in negatively charged amino acids such as glutamate and aspartate, while proteins binding to negatively charged molecules have surfaces rich in positively charged amino acids like lysine and arginine.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] For example, lysine and arginine are present in large amounts in the low-complexity regions of nucleic-acid binding proteins.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] There are various hydrophobicity scales of amino acid residues.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Some amino acids have special properties.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Cysteine can form covalent disulfide bonds to other cysteine residues.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Proline forms a cycle to the polypeptide backbone, and glycine is more flexible than other amino acids.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Glycine and proline are strongly present within low complexity regions of both eukaryotic and prokaryotic proteins, whereas the opposite is the case with cysteine, phenylalanine, tryptophan, methionine, valine, leucine, isoleucine, which are highly reactive, or complex, or hydrophobic.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] For example, a signaling protein can attach and then detach from a cell membrane, because it contains cysteine residues that can have the fatty acid palmitic acid added to them and subsequently removed.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The common natural forms of amino acids have a zwitterionic structure, with −NH+3 (−NH+2− in the case of proline) and −CO−2 functional groups attached to the same C atom, and are thus α-amino acids, and are the only ones found in proteins during translation in the ribosome.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] In aqueous solution at pH close to neutrality, amino acids are energetically favored in their zwitterionic form, with a deprotonated CO−2 group and a protonated NH+3 group, because the high dielectric constant of water and its hydrogen-bonding network effectively stabilize separated charges.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Thus, the overall structure is NH+3−CHR−CO−2, and the so-called "neutral forms" −NH2−CHR−CO2H are not present to any measurable degree at physiological pH.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] In strongly acidic conditions (pH below 3), the carboxylate group becomes protonated and the structure becomes an ammonio carboxylic acid, NH+3−CHR−CO2H.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] This is relevant for enzymes like pepsin that are active in acidic environments such as the mammalian stomach and lysosomes, but does not significantly apply to intracellular enzymes.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] In highly basic conditions (pH greater than 10, not normally seen in physiological conditions), the ammonio group is deprotonated to give NH2−CHR−CO−2.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Although various definitions of acids and bases are used in chemistry, the only one that is useful for chemistry in aqueous solution is that of Brønsted: an acid is a species that can donate a proton to another species, and a base is one that can accept a proton.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] This criterion is used to label the groups in the above illustration.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The carboxylate side chains of aspartate and glutamate residues are the principal Brønsted bases in proteins.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Likewise, lysine, tyrosine and cysteine will typically act as a Brønsted acid.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Histidine under these conditions can act both as a Brønsted acid and a base.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] For amino acids with uncharged side-chains the zwitterion predominates at pH values between the two p*K*a values, but coexists in equilibrium with small amounts of net negative and net positive ions.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] At the midpoint between the two p*K*a values, the trace amount of net negative and trace of net positive ions balance, so that average net charge of all forms present is zero.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] This pH is known as the isoelectric point p*I*, so p*I* = ⁠1/2⁠(p*K*a1 + p*K*a2).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] For amino acids with charged side chains, the p*K*a of the side chain is involved.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Thus for aspartate or glutamate with negative side chains, the terminal amino group is essentially entirely in the charged form −NH+3, but this positive charge needs to be balanced by the state with just one C-terminal carboxylate group is negatively charged.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] This occurs halfway between the two carboxylate p*K*a values: p*I* = ⁠1/2⁠(p*K*a1 + p*K*a(R)), where p*K*a(R) is the side chain p*K*a.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Similar considerations apply to other amino acids with ionizable side-chains, including not only glutamate (similar to aspartate), but also cysteine, histidine, lysine, tyrosine and arginine with positive side chains.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Amino acids have zero mobility in electrophoresis at their isoelectric point, although this behaviour is more usually exploited for peptides and proteins than single amino acids.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Zwitterionic amino acids exhibit minimal solubility at their isoelectric point, and in some cases can be isolated from aqueous solution by adjusting the pH to the appropriate isoelectric value.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Although one-letter symbols are included in the table, IUPAC–IUBMB recommend that "Use of the one-letter symbols should be restricted to the comparison of long sequences".
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] In addition to the specific amino acid codes, placeholders are used in cases where chemical or crystallographic analysis of a peptide or protein cannot conclusively determine the identity of a residue.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] They are also used to summarize conserved protein sequence motifs.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The use of single letters to indicate sets of similar residues is similar to the use of abbreviation codes for degenerate bases.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] In addition, many nonstandard amino acids have a specific code.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] For example, several peptide drugs, such as Bortezomib and MG132, are artificially synthesized and retain their protecting groups, which have specific codes.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Bortezomib is Pyz–Phe–boroLeu, and MG132 is Z–Leu–Leu–Leu–al.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] To aid in the analysis of protein structure, photo-reactive amino acid analogs are available.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] These include photoleucine (**pLeu**) and photomethionine (**pMet**).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Amino acids are the precursors to proteins.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] They join by condensation reactions to form short polymer chains called peptides or longer chains called either polypeptides or proteins.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] These chains are linear and unbranched, with each amino acid residue within the chain attached to two neighboring amino acids.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] In nature, the process of making proteins encoded by RNA genetic material is called *translation* and involves the step-by-step addition of amino acids to a growing protein chain by a ribozyme that is called a ribosome.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The order in which the amino acids are added is read through the genetic code from an mRNA template, which is an RNA derived from one of the organism's genes.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] There are 22 amino acids that get naturally incorporated into polypeptides; these are called *proteinogenic amino acids* or *natural amino acids*.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Of these, 20 are encoded by the universal genetic code.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The remaining 2, selenocysteine and pyrrolysine, are incorporated into proteins by unique synthetic mechanisms.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Selenocysteine is incorporated when the mRNA being translated includes a SECIS element, which causes the UGA codon to encode selenocysteine instead of a stop codon.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine is used by some methanogenic archaea in enzymes that they use to produce methane.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] It is coded for with the codon UAG, which is normally a stop codon in other organisms.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The 20 amino acids that are encoded directly by the codons of the universal genetic code are called *standard* or *canonical* amino acids.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] A modified form of methionine (*N*-formylmethionine) is often incorporated in place of methionine as the initial amino acid of proteins in bacteria, mitochondria and plastids (including chloroplasts).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Other amino acids are called *nonstandard* or *non-canonical*.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Most of the nonstandard amino acids are also non-proteinogenic (i.e. they cannot be incorporated into proteins during translation), but two of them are proteinogenic, as they can be incorporated translationally into proteins by exploiting information not encoded in the universal genetic code.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The two nonstandard proteinogenic amino acids are selenocysteine (present in many non-eukaryotes as well as most eukaryotes, but not coded directly by DNA) and pyrrolysine (found only in some archaea and at least one bacterium).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The incorporation of these nonstandard amino acids is rare.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] For example, 25 human proteins include selenocysteine in their primary structure, and the structurally characterized enzymes (selenoenzymes) employ selenocysteine as the catalytic moiety in their active sites.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine and selenocysteine are encoded via variant codons.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] For example, selenocysteine is encoded by stop codon and SECIS element.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Aside from the 22 proteinogenic amino acids, many *non-proteinogenic* amino acids are known.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] These either are not found in proteins (for example carnitine, GABA, ornithine) or are not produced directly and in isolation by standard cellular machinery.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] For example, hydroxyproline is synthesized from proline, and selenomethionine is produced by metabolic modification of methionine.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids that are found in proteins are formed by post-translational modification.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Such modifications can also determine the localization of the protein, e.g., the addition of long hydrophobic groups can cause a protein to bind to a phospholipid membrane.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Some non-proteinogenic amino acids are not found in proteins.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Examples include 2-aminoisobutyric acid and the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids often occur as intermediates in the metabolic pathways for standard amino acids – for example, ornithine and citrulline occur in the urea cycle, part of amino acid catabolism (see below).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] A rare exception to the dominance of α-amino acids in biology is the β-amino acid beta alanine (3-aminopropanoic acid), which is used in plants and microorganisms in the synthesis of pantothenic acid (vitamin B5), a component of coenzyme A.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Many proteinogenic and non-proteinogenic amino acids have biological functions beyond being precursors to proteins and peptides.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] In humans, amino acids also have important roles in diverse biosynthetic pathways.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Defenses against herbivores in plants sometimes employ amino acids.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] However, not all of the functions of other abundant nonstandard amino acids are known.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Animals ingest amino acids in the form of protein.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The protein is broken down into its constituent amino acids in the process of digestion.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The amino acids are then used to synthesize new proteins and other nitrogenous biomolecules, or they are further catabolized through oxidation to provide a source of energy.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The oxidation pathway starts with the removal of the amino group by a transaminase; the amino group is then fed into the urea cycle.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The other product of transamidation is a keto acid that enters the citric acid cycle.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Glucogenic amino acids can also be converted into glucose, through gluconeogenesis.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Of the 20 standard amino acids, nine (His, Ile, Leu, Lys, Met, Phe, Thr, Trp and Val) are called essential amino acids because the human body cannot synthesize them from other compounds at the level needed for normal growth, so they must be obtained from food.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] In addition, cysteine, tyrosine, and arginine are considered semiessential amino acids, and taurine a semi-essential aminosulfonic acid in children.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Some amino acids are conditionally essential for certain ages or medical conditions.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Essential amino acids may also vary from species to species.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The metabolic pathways that synthesize these monomers are not fully developed.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Amino acids are sometimes added to animal feed because some of the components of these feeds, such as soybeans, have low levels of some of the essential amino acids, especially of lysine, methionine, threonine, and tryptophan.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Likewise amino acids are used to chelate metal cations in order to improve the absorption of minerals from feed supplements.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The food industry is a major consumer of amino acids, especially glutamic acid, which is used as a flavor enhancer, and aspartame (aspartylphenylalanine 1-methyl ester), which is used as an artificial sweetener.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Amino acids are sometimes added to food by manufacturers to alleviate symptoms of mineral deficiencies, such as anemia, by improving mineral absorption and reducing negative side effects from inorganic mineral supplementation.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Amino acids are low-cost feedstocks used in chiral pool synthesis as enantiomerically pure building blocks.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Amino acids are used in the synthesis of some cosmetics.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The chelating ability of amino acids is sometimes used in fertilizers to facilitate the delivery of minerals to plants in order to correct mineral deficiencies, such as iron chlorosis.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] These fertilizers are also used to prevent deficiencies from occurring and to improve the overall health of the plants.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Amino acids have been considered as components of biodegradable polymers, which have applications as environmentally friendly packaging and in medicine in drug delivery and the construction of prosthetic implants.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] An interesting example of such materials is polyaspartate, a water-soluble biodegradable polymer that may have applications in disposable diapers and agriculture.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Due to its solubility and ability to chelate metal ions, polyaspartate is also being used as a biodegradable antiscaling agent and a corrosion inhibitor.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The commercial production of amino acids usually relies on mutant bacteria that overproduce individual amino acids using glucose as a carbon source.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Some amino acids are produced by enzymatic conversions of synthetic intermediates.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] 2-Aminothiazoline-4-carboxylic acid is an intermediate in one industrial synthesis of L-cysteine for example.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Aspartic acid is produced by the addition of ammonia to fumarate using a lyase.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] In plants, nitrogen is first assimilated into organic compounds in the form of glutamate, formed from alpha-ketoglutarate and ammonia in the mitochondrion.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] For other amino acids, plants use transaminases to move the amino group from glutamate to another alpha-keto acid.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] For example, aspartate aminotransferase converts glutamate and oxaloacetate to alpha-ketoglutarate and aspartate.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Other organisms use transaminases for amino acid synthesis, too.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Nonstandard amino acids are usually formed through modifications to standard amino acids.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] For example, homocysteine is formed through the transsulfuration pathway or by the demethylation of methionine via the intermediate metabolite *S*-adenosylmethionine, while hydroxyproline is made by a post translational modification of proline.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Microorganisms and plants synthesize many uncommon amino acids.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] For example, some microbes make 2-aminoisobutyric acid and lanthionine, which is a sulfide-bridged derivative of alanine.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Both of these amino acids are found in peptidic lantibiotics such as alamethicin.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] However, in plants, 1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic acid is a small disubstituted cyclic amino acid that is an intermediate in the production of the plant hormone ethylene.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The formation of amino acids and peptides is assumed to have preceded and perhaps induced the emergence of life on earth.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Amino acids can form from simple precursors under various conditions.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Surface-based chemical metabolism of amino acids and very small compounds may have led to the build-up of amino acids, coenzymes and phosphate-based small carbon molecules.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Amino acids and similar building blocks could have been elaborated into proto-peptides, with peptides being considered key players in the origin of life.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] In the famous Urey-Miller experiment, the passage of an electric arc through a mixture of methane, hydrogen, and ammonia produces a large number of amino acids.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Several hypotheses invoke the Strecker synthesis whereby hydrogen cyanide, simple aldehydes, ammonia, and water produce amino acids.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] According to a review, amino acids, and even peptides, "turn up fairly regularly in the various experimental broths that have been allowed to be cooked from simple chemicals.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] This is because nucleotides are far more difficult to synthesize chemically than amino acids." For a chronological order, it suggests that there must have been a 'protein world' or at least a 'polypeptide world', possibly later followed by the 'RNA world' and the 'DNA world'.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Codon–amino acids mappings may be the biological information system at the primordial origin of life on Earth.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] While amino acids and consequently simple peptides must have formed under different experimentally probed geochemical scenarios, the transition from an abiotic world to the first life forms is to a large extent still unresolved.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Amino acids undergo the reactions expected of the constituent functional groups.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] As both the amine and carboxylic acid groups of amino acids can react to form amide bonds, one amino acid molecule can react with another and become joined through an amide linkage.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] This polymerization of amino acids is what creates proteins.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] This condensation reaction yields the newly formed peptide bond and a molecule of water.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] In cells, this reaction does not occur directly; instead, the amino acid is first activated by attachment to a transfer RNA molecule through an ester bond.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] This aminoacyl-tRNA is produced in an ATP-dependent reaction carried out by an aminoacyl tRNA synthetase.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] This aminoacyl-tRNA is then a substrate for the ribosome, which catalyzes the attack of the amino group of the elongating protein chain on the ester bond.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] As a result of this mechanism, all proteins made by ribosomes are synthesized starting at their *N*-terminus and moving toward their *C*-terminus.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] However, not all peptide bonds are formed in this way.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] In a few cases, peptides are synthesized by specific enzymes.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] For example, the tripeptide glutathione is an essential part of the defenses of cells against oxidative stress.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] This peptide is synthesized in two steps from free amino acids.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] In the first step, gamma-glutamylcysteine synthetase condenses cysteine and glutamate through a peptide bond formed between the side chain carboxyl of the glutamate (the gamma carbon of this side chain) and the amino group of the cysteine.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] This dipeptide is then condensed with glycine by glutathione synthetase to form glutathione.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] In chemistry, peptides are synthesized by a variety of reactions.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] One of the most-used in solid-phase peptide synthesis uses the aromatic oxime derivatives of amino acids as activated units.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] These are added in sequence onto the growing peptide chain, which is attached to a solid resin support.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Libraries of peptides are used in drug discovery through high-throughput screening.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The combination of functional groups allow amino acids to be effective polydentate ligands for metal–amino acid chelates.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The side chains of amino acids can also undergo posttranslational chemical reactions.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Degradation of an amino acid often begins with transamination, in which its amino group is transferred to α-ketoglutarate, forming glutamate.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] This process involves transaminases, often the same enzymes used in amino acid synthesis.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] In many vertebrates, the amino group is subsequently released as ammonia and converted to urea via the urea cycle for excretion.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] However, amino acid degradation can result in uric acid or ammonia instead, depending on the organism.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] For example, serine dehydratase converts serine directly to pyruvate and ammonia.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] Amino acids are bidentate ligands, forming transition metal amino acid complexes.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The total nitrogen content of organic matter is mainly formed by the amino groups in proteins.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] The total Kjeldahl nitrogen (TKN) is a measure of nitrogen widely used in the analysis of (waste) water, soil, food, feed and organic matter in general.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/amino-acid] As the name suggests, the Kjeldahl method is applied.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] A fundamental problem in fungal systematics is the existence of teleomorphic and anamorphic stages in their life cycles.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] These morphs usually differ drastically in their phenotypic appearance, preventing a straightforward association of the asexual anamorph with the sexual teleomorph.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Moreover, fungal species can comprise multiple strains that can vary in their morphology or in traits such as carbon- and nitrogen utilisation, which has often led to their description as different species, eventually producing long lists of synonyms.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Fungal DNA barcoding can help to identify and associate anamorphic and teleomorphic stages of fungi, and through that to reduce the confusing multitude of fungus names.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] For this reason, mycologists were among the first to spearhead the investigation of species discrimination by means of DNA sequences, at least 10 years earlier than the DNA barcoding proposal for animals by Paul D.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Hebert and colleagues in 2003, who popularised the term "DNA barcoding".
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] The success of identification of fungi by means of DNA barcode sequences stands and falls with the quantitative (completeness) and qualitative (level of identification) aspect of the reference database.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Without a database covering a broad taxonomic range of fungi, many identification queries will not result in a satisfyingly close match.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Likewise, without a substantial curatorial effort to maintain the records at a high taxonomic level of identification, queries – even when they might have a close or exact match in the reference database – will not be informative if the closest match is only identified to phylum or class level.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Another crucial prerequisite for DNA barcoding is the ability to unambiguously trace the provenance of DNA barcode data back to the originally sampled specimen, the so-called voucher specimen.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] This is common practice in biology along with the description of new taxa, where the voucher specimens, on which the taxonomic description is based, become the type specimens.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] When the identity of a certain taxon (or a genetic sequence in the case of DNA barcoding) is in doubt, the original specimen can be re-examined to review and ideally solve the issue.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Voucher specimens should be clearly labelled as such, including a permanent voucher identifier that unambiguously connects the specimen with the DNA barcode data derived from it.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Furthermore, these voucher specimens should be deposited in publicly accessible repositories like scientific collections or herbaria to preserve them for future reference and to facilitate research involving the deposited specimens.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] In fungi, the Internal transcribed spacer (*ITS*) is a roughly 600 base pairs long region in the ribosomal tandem repeat gene cluster of the nuclear genome.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] The region is flanked by the DNA sequences for the ribosomal small subunit (SSU) or 18S subunit at the 5' end, and by the large subunit (LSU) or 28S subunit at the 3' end.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] The Internal Transcribed Spacer itself consists of two parts, *ITS1* and *ITS2*, which are separated from each other by the 5.8S subunit nested between them.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Like the flanking 18S and 28S subunits, the 5.8S subunit contains a highly conserved DNA sequence, as they code for structural parts of the ribosome, which is a key component in intracellular protein synthesis.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Due to several advantages of *ITS* (see below) and a comprehensive amount of sequence data accumulated in the 1990s and early 2000s, Begerow et al.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] (2012) proposed the *ITS* region as primary DNA barcode region for the genetic identification of fungi.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] UNITE is an open *ITS* barcoding database for fungi and all other eukaryotes.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] The conserved flanking regions of 18S and 28S serve as anchor points for the primers used for PCR amplification of the *ITS* region.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Moreover, the conserved nested 5.8S region allows for the construction of "internal" primers, i.e., primers attaching to complementary sequences within the ITS region.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] (1990) proposed such internal primers, named ITS2 and ITS3, along with the flanking primers ITS1 and ITS4 in the 18S and the 28S subunit, respectively.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Due to their almost universal applicability to ITS sequencing in fungi, these primers are still in wide use today.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Optimised primers specifically for ITS sequencing in Dikarya (comprising Basidiomycota and Ascomycota) have been proposed by Toju et al.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] For the majority of fungi, the ITS primers proposed by White et al.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] (1990) have become the standard primers used for PCR amplification (with the most common pairing being ITS1 + ITS4).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] A major advantage of using the ITS region as molecular marker and fungal DNA barcode is that the entire ribosomal gene cluster is arranged in tandem repeats, i.e., in multiple copies.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] This allows for its PCR amplification and Sanger sequencing even from small material samples (given the DNA is not fragmented due to age or other degenerative influences).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Hence, a high PCR success rate is usually observed when amplifying *ITS*.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] However, this success rate varies greatly among fungal groups, from 65% in non-Dikarya (including the now paraphyletic Mucoromycotina, the Chytridiomycota and the Blastocladiomycota) to 100% in Saccharomycotina and Basidiomycota (with the exception of very low success in Pucciniomycotina).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Furthermore, the choice of primers for *ITS* amplification can introduce biases towards certain taxonomic fungus groups.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] For example, the "universal" *ITS* primers fail to amplify about 10% of the tested fungal specimens.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] The tandem repeats of the ribosomal gene cluster cause the problem of significant intragenomic sequence heterogeneity observed among *ITS* copies of several fungal groups.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] In Sanger sequencing, this will cause *ITS* sequence reads of different lengths to superpose each other, potentially rendering the resulting chromatograph unreadable.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Furthermore, because of the non-coding nature of the *ITS* region that can lead to a substantial amount of indels, it is impossible to consistently align *ITS* sequences from highly divergent species for further bigger-scale phylogenetic analyses.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] The degree of intragenomic sequence heterogeneity can be investigated in more detail through molecular cloning of the initially PCR-amplified ITS sequences, followed by sequencing of the clones.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] However, this approach of sequencing after cloning was rarely done for the *ITS* sequences that make up the reference libraries used for DNA barcode-aided identification, thus potentially giving an underestimate of the existing *ITS* sequence variation in many samples.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] The weighted arithmetic mean of the intraspecific (within-species) *ITS* variability among fungi is 2.51%.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] This variability, however, can range from 0% for example in *Serpula lacrymans* (n=93 samples) over 0.19% in *Tuber melanosporum* (n=179) up to 15.72% in *Rhizoctonia solani* (n=608), or even 24.75% in *Pisolithus tinctorius* (n=113).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] In the case of medically relevant fungal species, a more strict threshold of 2.5% *ITS* variability allows only around 75% of all species to be accurately identified to the species level.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] On the other hand, morphologically well-defined, but evolutionarily young species complexes or sibling species may only differ (if at all) in a few nucleotides of the *ITS* sequences.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] For some taxa, *ITS* (or its *ITS2* part) is not variable enough as fungal DNA barcode, as for example has been shown in *Aspergillus*, *Cladosporium*, *Fusarium* and *Penicillium*.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Efforts to define a universally applicable threshold value of *ITS* variability that demarcates intraspecific from interspecific (between-species) variability thus remain futile.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Nonetheless, the probability of correct species identification with the *ITS* region is high in the Dikarya, and especially so in Basidiomycota, where even the *ITS1* part is often sufficient to identify the species.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] However, its discrimination power is partly superseded by that of the DNA-directed RNA polymerase II subunit *RPB1* (see also below).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Due to the shortcomings of ITS-based primary fungal DNA barcoding, the necessity of establishing a second DNA barcode marker was expressed.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Several attempts were made to establish other genetic markers that could serve as additional DNA barcodes, similar to the situation in plants, where the plastidial genes *rbcL*, *matK* and *trnH-psbA*, as well as the nuclear *ITS* are often used in combination for DNA barcoding.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] The translational elongation factor 1α is part of the eukaryotic elongation factor 1 complex, whose main function is to facilitate the elongation of the amino acid chain of a polypeptide during the translation process of gene expression.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] (2015) investigated the *TEF1α* gene, among a number of others, as potential genetic marker for fungal DNA barcoding.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] The *TEF1α* gene coding for the translational elongation factor 1α is generally considered to have a slow mutation rate, and it is therefore generally better suited for investigating older splits deeper in the phylogenetic history of an organism group.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Despite this, the authors conclude that *TEF1α* is the most promising candidate for an additional DNA barcode marker in fungi as it also features sequence regions of higher mutation rates.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Following this, a quality-controlled reference database was established and merged with the previously existing ISHAM-ITS database for fungal ITS DNA barcodes to form the ISHAM database.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Primers used for the investigation of Rhizophydiales and especially *Batrachochytrium dendrobatidis*, a pathogen of amphibia, are the forward primer *tef1F* with the nucleotide sequence 5'-TACAARTGYGGTGGTATYGACA-3', and the reverse primer *tef1R* with the sequence 5'-ACNGACTTGACYTCAGTRGT-3'.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] These primers also successfully amplified the majority of *Cantharellus* species investigated by Buyck et al.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] (2014), with the exception of a few species for which more specific primers were developed: the forward primer *tef-1Fcanth* with the sequence 5'-AGCATGGGTDCTYGACAAG-3', and the reverse primer *tef-1Rcanth* with the sequence 5'-CCAATYTTRTAYACATCYTGGAG-3'.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] The D1/D2 domain is part of the nuclear large subunit (28S) ribosomal RNA, and it is therefore located in the same ribosomal tandem repeat gene cluster as the Internal Transcribed Spacer (*ITS*).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] But unlike the non-coding ITS sequences, the D1/D2 domain contains coding sequence.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] With about 600 base pairs it is about the same nucleotide sequence length as *ITS*, which makes amplification and sequencing rather straightforward, an advantage that has led to the accumulation of an extensive amount of *D1/D2* sequence data especially for yeasts.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Regarding the molecular identification of basidiomycetous yeasts, *D1/D2* (or *ITS*) can be used alone.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] (2002) recommend the combined analysis of the *D1/D2* and *ITS* regions, a practice that later became the standard required information for describing new taxa of asco- and basidiomycetous yeasts.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] When attempting to identify early diverging fungal lineages, the study of Schoch et al.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] (2012), comparing the identification performance of different genetic markers, showed that the large subunit (as well as the small subunit) of the ribosomal RNA performs better than *ITS* or *RPB1*.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] For basidiomycetous yeasts, the forward primer *F63* with the sequence 5'-GCATATCAATAAGCGGAGGAAAAG-3', and the reverse primer *LR3* with the sequence 5'-GGTCCGTGTTTCAAGACGG-3' have been successfully used for PCR amplification of the D1/D23 domain.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] The D1/D2 domain of ascomycetous yeasts like *Candida* can be amplified with the forward primer *NL-1* (same as *F63*) and the reverse primer *NL-4* (same as *LR3*).
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] The RNA polymerase II subunit *RPB1* is the largest subunit of the RNA polymerase II.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] In *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*, it is encoded by the *RPO21* gene.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] PCR amplification success of *RPB1* is very taxon-dependent, ranging from 70 to 80% in Ascomycota to 14% in early diverging fungal lineages.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Apart from the early diverging lineages, *RPB1* has a high rate of species identification in all fungal groups.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] In the species-rich Pezizomycotina it even outperforms ITS.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] In a study comparing the identification performance of four genes, *RPB1* was among the most effective genes when combining two genes in the analysis: combined analysis with either *ITS* or with the large subunit ribosomal RNA yielded the highest identification success.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Other studies also used RPB2, the second-largest subunit of the RNA polymerase II, e.g. for studying the phylogenetic relationships among species of the genus *Cantharellus* or for a phylogenetic study shedding light on the relationships among early-diverging lineages in the fungal kingdom.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Primers successfully amplifying RPB1 especially in Ascomycota are the forward primer *RPB1-Af* with the sequence 5'-GARTGYCCDGGDCAYTTYGG-3', and the reverse primer *RPB1-Ac-RPB1-Cr* with the sequence 5'-CCNGCDATNTCRTTRTCCATRTA-3'.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] The Intergenic Spacer (*IGS*) is the region of non-coding DNA between individual tandem repeats of the ribosomal gene cluster in the nuclear genome, as opposed to the Internal Transcribed Spacer (ITS) that is situated within these tandem repeats.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] The recent discovery of additional non-coding RNA genes in the IGS region of some basidiomycetes cautions against uncritical use of *IGS* sequences for DNA barcoding and phylogenetic purposes.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] The **cytochrome c oxidase subunit I (*COI*)** gene outperforms *ITS* in DNA barcoding of *Penicillium* (Ascomycota) species, with species-specific barcodes for 66% of the investigated species versus 25% in the case of *ITS*.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Furthermore, a part of the β-Tubulin A (*BenA*) gene exhibits a higher taxonomic resolution in distinguishing *Penicillium* species as compared to *COI* and *ITS*.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] In the closely related *Aspergillus niger* complex, however, *COI* is not variable enough for species discrimination.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] In *Fusarium*, *COI* exhibits paralogues in many cases, and homologous copies are not variable enough to distinguish species.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Like *TOP1*, the **Phosphoglycerate kinase (*PGK*)** was among the genetic markers investigated by Lewis et al.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] (2015) as potential additional fungal DNA barcodes.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] A number of universal primers was developed, with the PGK533 primer pair, amplifying a circa 1,000 base pair fragment, being the most successful in most fungi except Basidiomycetes.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Like *TOP1*, *PGK* is superior to *ITS* in species differentiation in ascomycete genera like *Penicillium* and *Fusarium*, and both *PGK* and *TOP1* perform as good as *TEF1α* in distinguishing closely related species in these genera.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] A citizen science project investigated the consensus between the labelling of dried, commercially sold mushrooms and the DNA barcoding results from these mushrooms.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] All samples were found to be correctly labelled.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] However, an obstacle was the unreliability of ITS reference databases in terms of the level of identification, as the two databases (GenBank and UNITE) used for ITS sequence comparison gave different identification results in some of the samples.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Correct labelling of mushrooms intended for consumption was also investigated by Raja et al.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] (2016), who used the *ITS* region for DNA barcoding from dried mushrooms, mycelium powders, and dietary supplement capsules.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] In only 30% of the 33 samples did the product label correctly state the binomial fungus name.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] In another 30%, the genus name was correct, but the species epithet did not match, and in 15% of the cases not even the genus name of the binomial name given on the product label matched the result of the obtained *ITS* barcode.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] For the remaining 25% of the samples, no *ITS* sequence could be obtained.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] (2019) focused on the identification accuracy of pathogenic fungi using both the primary (*ITS*) and secondary (*TEF1α*) barcode markers.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Their results show that in *Diutina* (a segregate of *Candida*) and *Pichia*, species identification is straightforward with either the *ITS* or the *TEF1α* as well as with a combination of both.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] *TEF1α*, on the other hand, allowed identification of all investigated species of the *Lodderomyces* clade.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Similar results were obtained for *Scedosporium* species, which are attributed to a wide range of localised to invasive diseases: *ITS* could not distinguish between *S. apiospermum* and *S. boydii*, whereas with *TEF1α* all investigated species of this genus could be accurately identified.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] This study therefore underlines the usefulness of applying more than one DNA barcoding marker for fungal species identification.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Fungal DNA barcoding has been successfully applied to the investigation of foxing phenomena, a major concern in the conservation of paper documents.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Another study investigated fungi that act as biodeteriorating agents in the Old Cathedral of Coimbra, part of the University of Coimbra, a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Sequencing the *ITS* barcode of ten samples with classical Sanger as well as with Illumina next-generation sequencing techniques, they identified 49 fungal species.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] *Aspergillus versicolor*, *Cladosporium cladosporioides*, *C. sphaerospermum*, *C. tenuissimum*, *Epicoccum nigrum*, *Parengyodontium album*, *Penicillium brevicompactum*, *P. crustosum*, *P. glabrum*, *Talaromyces amestolkiae* and *T. stollii* were the most common species isolated from the samples.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Another study concerning objects of cultural heritage investigated the fungal diversity on a canvas painting by Paula Rego using the *ITS2* subregion of the *ITS* marker.
[src:fungal-dna-barcoding/fungal-dna-barcoding] Altogether, 387 OTUs (putative species) in 117 genera of 13 different classes of fungi were observed.
